Allstate\'s approach is to safeguard our customers while having \nsustainable business practices and adequate returns. Increased severe weather has raised loss costs for auto and homeowners insurance, requiring \nchanges in pricing, product coverages, underwriting practices and reinsurance utilization. Impacts will continue due to the increase in severe weather \ndriven by climate change.  \nAllstate is addressing climate risk by prioritizing three major areas that impact our customers and business: \n1) Disaster Prevention, Preparedness and Risk Response – We have partnered with federal and state governments for over two\ndecades to create programs to help provide protection for insureds most exposed to climate change. This has been accomplished\nthrough the establishment of entities like Florida Citizens, the Florida Hurricane Catastrophe Fund, the Texas Windstorm Insurance\nAssociation and the California Earthquake Authority.\n2) Monitoring and Managing Climate Risk – Our business success depends on effectively modeling, pricing and managing climate-\nrelated risks, and developing products and services to address the impact of severe weather. We identify, measure, manage and\nmonitor material risks, including climate change, through a risk evaluation framework which is reviewed by the Board of Directors.\nInsurability – Estimates of losses from major catastrophes are modeled to assess risk levels and appropriate pricing.\nUnderwriting – Frequency and severity of events are managed through pricing, underwriting and reinsurance.\n3) Reducing Our Carbon Footprint Across Allstate – We have cut energy use beyond our original targets and reduced our greenhouse\ngas (GHG) emissions. We also converted half of our fleet of sedans and SUVs in the U.S. and Canada to hybrid vehicles, and 100% of the\npower used at our Northbrook, Illinois headquarters and our Irving, Texas office qualifies for Renewable Energy Certificates.\nThe investment portfolio is monitored for both short- and long-term potential exposures to environmental risks, including climate change. Across the \nportfolio, we classify sectors\' potential exposure to environmental risks. We consider potential environmental risks when we assess the size and \nmaturity profile of our positions. Many holdings in sectors with higher potential exposure are invested in public markets, providing flexibility to adjust \nexposures as risk and return trade-offs evolve. For commercial real estate, we classify our investments based on their modeled exposure to certain \ncatastrophe risks and incorporate these risks in our practices. \n\nRisks within the Investment Portfolio \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##About this Report \n\nAllstate is providing the following table that indicates where readers can find disclosures within publicly available documents that address the \nrecommendations of the Task Force on Climate-Related Financial Disclosures (TCFD). Allstate intends to further align its disclosures with the \nrecommendations of the TCFD by completing scenario analysis work already underway. Allstate intends to have its science-based target (SBT) \nscenarios for Scope 1 and 2 emissions completed during the second half of 2021. Scope 3 SBT scenarios are focused on the climate impact of our \ninvestment portfolio. Allstate intends to also complete its initial Scope 3 review during the second half of 2021 and plans to submit its intent to establish \nan emissions reduction target based on the Guidance for Financial Institutions from the Science Based Targets Initiative (SBTI-FI), focused on the IPCC \nguidance consistent with a well-below 2°C pathway, by the end of 2021. \n\nTCFD Index \n\nRecommended Disclosures \n\nGovernance \n\na)Describe the board’s oversight of climate-\nrelated risks and opportunities.\n\nb)Describe management’s role in assessing\nand managing climate-related risks and\nopportunities.\n\nResponse/Comment \n\nThe Board has oversight of all risk and return activities and reviews environmental, social and \ngovernance (ESG) matters to prioritize efforts twice a year.  Two committees are also responsible for \nadditional oversight:  Nominating, Governance and Social Responsibility Committee and Risk and \nReturn Committee. \nThe Board\'s Nominating, Governance and Social Responsibility Committee oversees ESG priorities, \nstrategy and reporting. \nThe Board\'s Risk and Return Committee oversees climate change risks and opportunities through the \nlens of Allstate\'s Enterprise Risk and Return Management (ERRM) framework. The Risk and Return \nCommittee conducted a thorough review of Allstate\'s climate risk and return management approach in \n2020 and 2021. \nFor a full description of our Board\'s oversight of climate risk, please see 2021 Proxy Statement, pg. 36, \nand CDP Climate Change Responses, C1.1, C1.1a, C1.1b. \nThe Enterprise Risk and Return Council (ERRC) meets monthly and is Allstate’s senior risk \nmanagement committee below Board level. The ERRC is made up of Allstate’s CEO, vice chair, chief \ninvestment officer, general counsel, treasurer, area of responsibility (AOR) presidents and enterprise \nand AOR risk and financial officers.   It supports ERRM by establishing risk and return targets, \ndetermining economic capital levels, and directing integrated strategies and actions from an enterprise \nperspective. The Chief Risk Officer chairs the ERRC and ensures that it performs its duties, and reports \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##to the CEO.  Business areas identify, measure, manage, monitor and report on risks at a granular level, \nincluding climate risks, and risks in excess of limits or tolerances are reported regularly to the ERRC \nand Board\'s Risk and Return Committee in the ERRM Summary Report.  For a more detailed \ndescription of our ERRM framework, see pgs. 104-106 of the Annual Report on Form 10-K. \nAllstate also maintains a Sustainability Council that was formed in 2007. Its cross-functional members \nidentify key risks and opportunities related to sustainable business practices and help implement \nAllstate’s enterprise ESG road map. The council, with 40 members representing more than 25 business \nfunctions, meets regularly and is led by a vice president in Corporate Brand. The council updates \nsenior executives periodically. \nOn the Investments side, the Responsible Investing Committee monitors ESG investing trends and best \npractices and periodically reports about its activities to other leaders within Allstate. This Committee \nalso monitors the investment portfolio for short- and potential long-term exposures to climate change.  \nDifferent sectors are classified based on exposure to environmental risks, including climate change, \nand environmental risks are incorporated in the sizing and maturity profile of our positions.  Sectors \nwith higher potential exposure are primarily invested in public markets, providing flexibility to adjust \nexposures.  Commercial real estate investments are classified based on their modeled exposure to \ncatastrophe risks. \nFor additional information regarding management’s role in assessing and managing climate-related \nrisks and opportunities, see CDP Climate Change Responses, C1.2, C1.2a, C-FS2.2b, 2021 Proxy \nStatement, pg. 36, and Accountability under the Climate Strategy and Disaster Resiliency section of our \nSustainability Report. \nRisks and return opportunities are evaluated across six key categories (strategic, insurance, financial, \ninvestment, operational, and culture) with climate impacting all six areas. Increased severe weather \nhas raised loss costs for auto and homeowners insurance, requiring changes in pricing, product \ncoverages, underwriting practices and reinsurance utilization. Impacts will continue to evolve due to \nthe increasing effect of severe weather driven by climate change.  Physical and transition risks exist \nwithin the investment portfolio, along with opportunities associated with “green” investments and \nemerging technologies. See 2021 Proxy Statement, pgs. 12-13 and Year in Review, pg. 13. \nFor a more complete description of risks and opportunities identified, please see CDP Climate Change \n\nStrategy \n\na)Describe the climate-related risks and\nopportunities the organization has identified\nover the short, medium, and long term.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##b)Describe the impact of climate-related\nrisks and opportunities on the organization’s\nbusinesses, strategy, and financial planning.\n\nResponses, C2.2, C2.2a, C-FS2.2b, C-FS2.2c, C-FS2.2d, C-FS2.2e, C2.3b, C2.4b, and the Risk Factors \nsection of the Annual Report on Form 10-K, pgs. 22-30, for a list of risks impacting Allstate. \nManaging climate-related risks and opportunities has been a priority at Allstate for 25 years as it \nimpacts all aspects of our business, particularly homeowners insurance.  We have worked to mitigate \nthe effect of more severe weather on customers’ homes and shareholder returns, which has impacted \nwhere we provide protection, what the protection covers, pricing, utilization of risk reduction efforts \nsuch as reinsurance, provision of third party products, and regulatory and compliance initiatives. \nSubstantial progress has been made to make homes safer through better building codes, and to \nimprove affordability by pooling risks and modifying our business practices. As the climate continues \nto change, this expertise will serve customers and shareholders well, and Allstate will continue to \nadjust its strategy and risk profile to protect shareholders, customers, and its reputation. \nThe Board’s Risk and Return Committee reviewed the impact of climate change on the company\'s \nshort- and long-term strategies in 2020 and 2021 See Letter from the Independent Directors in 2021 \nProxy Statement, pg. 4. \nThe catastrophe reinsurance program is part of Allstate\'s catastrophe management strategy. For \ninformation about the reinsurance program, see Risk Management section below. \nIn 2020, Allstate\'s Investment Management Committee adopted a Responsible Investing Policy that \noutlines expectations for Investment professionals to consider available data for ESG-related factors \nwhen making investment decisions. Allstate expects its Investment professionals to refrain from \nmaking certain types of investments that may result in significant ESG-related risks. In addition to the \nResponsible Investing Policy, the Investment Management Guidelines state that Investment managers\' \nanalysis and decision-making consider ESG issues when assessing risk/return trade-offs for a \nparticular investment. Allstate Investments\' compliance department maintains a restricted list that \ndefines prohibited types of investments, which are typically entities whose activities are \nfundamentally inconsistent with Allstate\'s values or are likely to result in reputational or other \nsignificant risks. \nFor more information on how climate-related risks and opportunities have influenced Allstate\'s \nbusinesses, strategy and financial planning, please see CDP Climate Change Responses, C3.1d, C3.1e, C-\nFS3.2a, C-FS3.2b, C-FS3.3a. \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##c)Describe the resiliency of the\norganization’s strategy, taking into\nconsideration different climate-related\nscenarios, including a 2 degree Celsius or\nlower scenario.\n\nWe analyze the potential impact of climate-related changes as part of the strategic planning process. \nAllstate’s strategy to increase market share in the personal property-liability business and expand \nprotections offerings for customers is resistant to increased severe weather.  After experiencing severe \ncatastrophe losses in 2004 and 2005, Allstate repositioned the homeowners business, which is now \nconsistently profitable.  Along with changing product details and underwriting practices, the company \ncreated a comprehensive catastrophe reinsurance program to reduce certain risks. \nAdditionally, Allstate’s Catastrophe Modeling and Analytics Team and Pricing Groups monitor climate \nchange information as part of their analysis of weather-related trends. Models developed internally \nand by third-party vendors are used along with Allstate\'s historical data in assessing property \ninsurance exposure to catastrophe losses. Losses and changes in exposure are analyzed and reported \nto senior leaders each quarter. Allstate\'s internal stress tests focus on predicting business continuity, \nresiliency and solvency through a variety of catastrophe scenarios. The Catastrophe Modeling and \nAnalytics Team also partners with the Investments group to model the catastrophe exposure of real \nestate investments and portfolios. \nAllstate measures and monitors insurance risk (which includes claims frequency and severity and \ncatastrophes and severe weather) with different approaches, including stochastic methods and \nscenario analysis. For additional details related to the reserving process for property and casualty \ninsurance claims, see pgs. 111-118 of the Annual Report on Form 10-K. \nFor a full description of Allstate\'s process, please see CDP Climate Change Responses, C3.1a, 3.1b, and \nPolicies and Procedures under the Climate Strategy and Disaster Resiliency section of our \nSustainability Report. \nWork is underway to complete our full climate change scenario analysis. We will update this report \nwith further information as soon as it is available. \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Risk Management \n\na)Describe the organization’s processes\nfor identifying and assessing climate-\nrelated risks.\n\nb)Describe the organization’s processes\nfor managing climate-related risks.\n\nWe manage climate change risk as part of the ERRM program. Enterprise risks and opportunities are \nidentified, prioritized, measured, managed, monitored, and reported under an integrated ERRM \nframework, which includes our risk appetite statement, Risk and Return Principles, key risk and \nreturn categories, governance, modeling, analytics, and transparent management dialogue.  The \nBoard’s Risk and Return Committee also annually assesses risk associated with extremely low \nfrequency scenarios \nFor a full description of risks and opportunities identified, please see CDP Climate Change Responses, \nC2.2, C2.2a, C-FS2.2b, C-FS2.2c, C-FS2.2d, C-FS2.2e, C-FS2.2f, C2.3, C2.3b, C2.4, C2.4b. \nFor additional information regarding our climate management process, please see Proxy Statement, \npgs. 12-13; and Policies and Procedures under the Climate Strategy and Disaster Resiliency section of \nour Sustainability Report. \nFor information regarding how Allstate manages climate risks and opportunities in our investment \nportfolio and our operational emission reduction initiatives, please see CDP Climate Change \nResponses, C-FS3.2, C-FS3.2a, C-FS3.2b, C-FS3.3, C-FS3.3a, C4.3, C4.3a, C4.3b, C4.3c, C4.5, C4.5a. \nOn an ongoing basis, Allstate identifies, assesses, mitigates, reports and monitors material risks, \nincluding climate change, through our integrated ERRM program. This enables holistic management \nof key risks and incorporates risk and return management into our business model.  The ERRM \nprogram includes our risk appetite statement, Risk and Return Principles, key risk and return \ncategories, governance, modeling, analytics, and transparent management dialogue. Risks that are \nconsidered material are escalated to senior management and the Board.  \nAllstate manages property risks through pricing, underwriting and reinsurance. This includes: \npurchasing multi-year reinsurance protection as well as aggregate coverage,\nlimiting new business for personal lines auto and property insurance in areas most exposed\nto hurricanes,\nimplementing tropical cyclone and/or wind/hail deductibles or exclusions where\nappropriate, and\npartnering with federal and state governments for over 25 years to create programs to\nprovide protection for insureds most exposed to climate change.\n\n•\n•\n\n•\n\n•\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##The catastrophe reinsurance program is part of Allstate\'s catastrophe management strategy, which is \nintended to provide shareholders with an acceptable return on the risks assumed in the personal \nlines business, reduce earnings variability, and provide protection to customers. It includes coverage \nfor losses to personal lines property, personal lines automobile, commercial lines property or \ncommercial lines automobile arising out of multiple perils, in addition to hurricanes and earthquakes. \nThe program continues to support a risk tolerance framework that targets less than a 1% likelihood \nof annual aggregate catastrophe losses from hurricanes and earthquakes, net of reinsurance, \nexceeding $2 billion, based on model assumptions currently used. The program materially reduces \nexposure to catastrophe losses and employs a multi-year approach to lessen the amount of \nreinsurance being placed in the market in any one year. See our Investor Relations website for our \nReinsurance Update.  \nOn the Investments side, investment physical risks are managed through modeling, underwriting and \ninsurance, and investment portfolio exposure is managed through credit research and liquidity. \nRisks and return opportunities are evaluated across six key categories: strategic, insurance, financial, \ninvestments, operational, and culture.  Climate change impacts all of these categories:   \nStrategic: changes to property construction trends and the transportation system create risks\nand opportunities,\nInsurance:  rising severe weather and precipitation levels impact loss trends for auto and\nhomeowners insurance, and increase the overall market size for homeowners insurance,\nFinancial:  liquidity and capital levels must be considered relative to catastrophe losses,\nInvestments:  there are risk implications for specific holdings and sectors, as well as\nopportunities in "green" investing,\nOperational:  considerations include regulatory compliance, model accuracy and business\ncontinuity, and\nCulture:  employees are establishing higher standards for acting in the best interest of\nsociety.\nFor additional information, please see pgs. 104-106 of the Annual Report on Form 10-K and CDP \nClimate Change responses, C2.2, C2.2a, C2.3b, and C2.4b. \n\n•\n•\n\n•\n\n•\n\n•\n\n•\n\nc)Describe how processes for\nidentifying, assessing, and managing\nclimate-related risks are integrated into\nthe organization’s overall risk\nmanagement.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Metrics and Targets \n\na)Disclose the metrics used by the\norganization to assess climate-related risks\nand opportunities in line with its strategy and\nrisk management process.\nb)Disclose Scope 1, Scope 2, and, if\nappropriate, Scope 3 greenhouse gas (GHG)\nemissions, and the related risks.\nc)Describe the targets used by the\norganization to manage climate-related risks\nand opportunities and performance against\ntargets.\n\nPlease see 2020 Form 10-K, which discloses annual catastrophe losses, effect of catastrophe losses on \ncombined ratio in total and by line of business, catastrophe losses and reserve re-estimates by line of \nbusiness, and catastrophe loss by size and type of event.  See pgs. 41, 43-48 of the Annual Report on \nForm 10-K. \nFor information regarding the metrics for our operational climate impact, please see information \nunder Policies and Procedures in the Operational Footprint section of our Sustainability Report. \nFor our emissions data, please see CDP Climate Change Responses, C6.1, C6.2, C6.3, C6.5, C6.10, C7.9a, \nC7.9b. \nOur emissions data is also available in the Operational Footprint section of our Sustainability Report. \nRisks exist; however, management of these risks is fully integrated into our business model. For information \nabout our absolute emissions target that we achieved previously, please see CDP Climate Change \nResponses, C4.1, C4.1a, and Policies and Procedures in the Operational Footprint section of our \nSustainability Report. \nAllstate intends to have its SBT scenarios for Scope 1 and 2 emissions completed during the second \nhalf of 2021. Scope 3 SBT scenarios focus on the climate impact of its investment portfolio. Natural Language Processing¶

Extracting content by pages and sentences¶

  1. Only properly structured sentences are extracted. Sentences that start with a Capital Letter and ends with a period. Sentences that are less than 10 words or more than 50 words are ignored.
  2. Pages with less than 500 words are excluded from extraction. Would like to focus on pages with mostly text content. This should exclude pages like cover and last page. It should also exclude pages that are more graphical with short notes and comments.
In [64]:
def run_NLP(content):

    def sent_to_words(sentences):
        for sentence in sentences:
            yield(gensim.utils.simple_preprocess(str(sentence), deacc=True))  # deacc=True removes punctuations

    # Define functions for stopwords, bigrams, trigrams and lemmatization
    def remove_stopwords(texts):
        return [[word for word in simple_preprocess(str(doc)) if word not in stop_words] for doc in texts]

    def make_bigrams(texts):
        return [bigram_mod[doc] for doc in texts]

    def make_trigrams(texts):
        return [trigram_mod[bigram_mod[doc]] for doc in texts]

    def lemmatization(texts, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV']):
        """https://spacy.io/api/annotation"""
        texts_out = []
        for sent in texts:
            doc = nlp(" ".join(sent)) 
            texts_out.append([token.lemma_ for token in doc if token.pos_ in allowed_postags])
        return texts_out

    data_words = list(sent_to_words(content))

    # Build the bigram and trigram models
    bigram = gensim.models.Phrases(data_words, min_count=5, threshold=100) # higher threshold fewer phrases.
    trigram = gensim.models.Phrases(bigram[data_words], threshold=100)  

    # Faster way to get a sentence clubbed as a trigram/bigram
    bigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(bigram)
    trigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(trigram)

    # Remove Stop Words
    data_words_nostops = remove_stopwords(data_words)

    # Form Bigrams
    data_words_bigrams = make_bigrams(data_words_nostops)

    # Do lemmatization keeping only noun, adj, vb, adv
    data_lemmatized = lemmatization(data_words_bigrams, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV'])
    
    return data_lemmatized

def run_NLP(content):

    def sent_to_words(sentences):
        for sentence in sentences:
            yield(gensim.utils.simple_preprocess(str(sentence), deacc=True))  # deacc=True removes punctuations

    # Define functions for stopwords, bigrams, trigrams and lemmatization
    def remove_stopwords(texts):
        return [[word for word in simple_preprocess(str(doc)) if word not in stop_words] for doc in texts]

    def make_bigrams(texts):
        return [bigram_mod[doc] for doc in texts]

    def make_trigrams(texts):
        return [trigram_mod[bigram_mod[doc]] for doc in texts]

    def lemmatization(texts, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV']):
        """https://spacy.io/api/annotation"""
        texts_out = []
        for sent in texts:
            doc = nlp(" ".join(sent)) 
            texts_out.append([token.lemma_ for token in doc if token.pos_ in allowed_postags])
        return texts_out

    data_words = list(sent_to_words(content))

    # Build the bigram and trigram models
    bigram = gensim.models.Phrases(data_words, min_count=5, threshold=100) # higher threshold fewer phrases.
    trigram = gensim.models.Phrases(bigram[data_words], threshold=100)  

    # Faster way to get a sentence clubbed as a trigram/bigram
    bigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(bigram)
    trigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(trigram)

    # Remove Stop Words
    data_words_nostops = remove_stopwords(data_words)

    # Form Bigrams
    data_words_bigrams = make_bigrams(data_words_nostops)

    # Do lemmatization keeping only noun, adj, vb, adv
    data_lemmatized = lemmatization(data_words_bigrams, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV'])
    
    return data_lemmatized

# context specific keywords not to include in topic modelling
fsi_stop_words = [
  'plc', 'group', 'target',
  'track', 'capital', 'holding',
  'report', 'annualreport',
  'esg', 'bank', 'report',
  'annualreport', 'long', 'make'
]

fsi_stop_words.append(report_company)
fsi_stop_words.append('apple')

# our list contains all english stop words + companies names + specific keywords
stop_words = stop_words.union(fsi_stop_words)

from wordcloud import WordCloud

# aggregate all 7200 records into one large string to run wordcloud on term frequency
large_string = ' '.join(report_sentences_lemma)

# use 3rd party lib to compute term freq., apply stop words
word_cloud = WordCloud(
    background_color="white",
    max_words=5000, 
    width=1500, 
    height=1000, 
    stopwords=stop_words, 
    contour_width=3, 
    contour_color='steelblue'
)

# display our wordcloud across all records
plt.figure(figsize=(16,16))
word_cloud.generate(large_string)
plt.imshow(word_cloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis("off")
plt.show()

# Extract bi-grams names
words = bigram_tf_idf_vectorizer.get_feature_names()

# extract our top 10 ngrams
total_counts = np.zeros(len(words))
for t in bigram_tf_idf:
    total_counts += t.toarray()[0]

count_dict = (zip(words, total_counts))
count_dict = sorted(count_dict, key=lambda x:x[1], reverse=True)[0:30]
words = [w[0] for w in count_dict]
counts = [w[1] for w in count_dict]
x_pos = np.arange(len(words))

Topic Modeling and Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA)¶

Evaluaton Metrics

  1. Perplexity: Captures how surprised a model is of new data it has not seen before, and is measured as the normalized log-likelihood of a held-out test set. Lower the better.
  2. Coherence Score: Measures score a single topic by measuring the degree of semantic similarity between high scoring words in the topic. Higher the better.

In the analysis, the model with the highest coherence score is selected as the optimal model.

In [78]:

id2word = corpora.Dictionary(data_lemmatized)

# Term Document Frequency
corpus = [id2word.doc2bow(text) for text in texts]

In [81]:
results = []
optimal_score = 0
optimal_model = None

for num_of_topics in tqdm(range(2,15,1)):
    
    result = {}
    
    # Build LDA model
    lda_model = gensim.models.ldamodel.LdaModel(corpus=corpus,
                                                id2word=id2word,
                                                num_topics=num_of_topics, 
                                                random_state=42,
                                                update_every=1,
                                                chunksize=5,
                                                passes=20,
                                                alpha='auto',
                                                per_word_topics=True) 

    coherence_model_lda = CoherenceModel(model=lda_model, texts=data_lemmatized, dictionary=id2word, coherence='c_v')
    
    if optimal_score < coherence_model_lda.get_coherence():
        optimal_score = coherence_model_lda.get_coherence()
        optimal_model = lda_model

    result['num_of_topics'] = num_of_topics
    result['perplexity'] = lda_model.log_perplexity(corpus)
    result['coherence_score'] = coherence_model_lda.get_coherence()
    
    results.append(result)
    
results = pd.DataFrame(results)  
results.set_index('num_of_topics', inplace=True)

    cloud.generate_from_frequencies(topic_words, max_font_size=300)
    plt.gca().imshow(cloud)
    plt.gca().set_title(topic_names[i], fontdict=dict(size=16))
    plt.gca().axis('off')

Closing Notes¶

  1. This is only a simple analysis that studies the ESG topics in only one ESG report. This study can be extended to more reports issued by the many companies across different sectors and industries.
  2. We can expect the number of topics to increase when more ESG reports are included in the study.
  3. Once relevant ESG topics are identified, then we can potentially calculate ESG scores by topics for all companies. Then we can assess and see whether such ESG score derived through NLP process correlates with the score given by rating agencies downloaded from yahoo finance.
